    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:175122a4-4999-4dd4-8e62-7cb5287a27f0",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a bright-eyed, curly-haired 4-year-old girl who walks into the pediatric clinic clinging tightly to her mother's hand. She is visibly uncomfortable, with flushed cheeks, watery eyes, and a persistent wet, productive cough that rattles with each breath. She occasionally winces when she coughs and instinctively presses her little hands to her chest. Despite being clearly unwell, she still clutches a small stuffed bunny toy that goes everywhere with her.\n\nAt home, {patientName} is a lively and energetic child who loves finger-painting, dancing to cartoon music, and playing pretend kitchen with her older brother. She attends a local daycare five days a week, where she is known to be very social and affectionate with her friends. Her symptoms began about five days ago with a runny nose and mild fever, but over the past two days the cough has become increasingly deep and frequent, disrupting her sleep and appetite.\n\n{patientName} lives in a mid-sized urban apartment with her parents and 7-year-old brother. Her father is a bus driver and her mother works part-time as a school aide. The household does not include any smokers, but the apartment building is older and has some known humidity issues. {patientName} generally has a good appetite for fruits, pasta, and soup, though she has been refusing most solid foods since falling ill. She is up to date on her routine childhood vaccinations.\n\nHer mother reports that {patientName} has been waking up multiple times per night coughing, and that her breathing sounds \"noisy.\" She has been mildly wheezy at times, particularly in the early morning. Her fever has been low-grade and manageable at home with antipyretics, but the persistent cough and reduced oral intake prompted her parents to seek medical attention today."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:2149557a-3147-41a8-ac82-95b1b1a6a908",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no significant prior chronic medical conditions. She experienced one episode of upper respiratory tract infection at age 2 that resolved without complications, and a brief febrile illness at age 3 that did not require hospitalization. There is no documented history of asthma, eczema, or recurrent wheezing, although today's presentation includes mild bronchospasm consistent with post-viral airway hyperreactivity. She attends daycare regularly, which is a known risk factor for recurrent respiratory infections in early childhood. {patientName} has no surgical history. Her immunization record is complete for her age group, including influenza and pneumococcal vaccines. She has a known allergy to penicillin (urticaria). Family history is notable for paternal asthma and a maternal grandmother with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. {patientName} is not on any regular medications at baseline. She lives in a household with no tobacco smoke exposure but with potential environmental humidity and mold triggers."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
